04336nmm a2200601Ia 9780801463488DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20112012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014634887 a10.7591/97808014634882doi  a(DE-B1597)478580  a(OCoLC)979577329  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE99.S8bW54 2008eb04a974.4 0049734492221 aWheeler, Rachel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTo Live upon Hope :bMohicans and Missionaries in the Eighteenth-Century Northeast /cRachel Wheeler. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b2 maps, 9 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTwo Northeast Indian communities with similar histories of colonization accepted Congregational and Moravian missionaries, respectively, within five years of one another: the Mohicans of Stockbridge, Massachusetts (1735), and Shekomeko, in Dutchess County, New York (1740). In To Live upon Hope, Rachel Wheeler explores the question of what "missionary Christianity" became in the hands of these two native communities.The Mohicans of Stockbridge and Shekomeko drew different conclusions from their experiences with colonial powers. Both tried to preserve what they deemed core elements of Mohican culture. The Indians of Stockbridge believed education in English cultural ways was essential to their survival and cast their acceptance of the mission project as a means of preserving their historic roles as cultural intermediaries. The Mohicans of Shekomeko, by contrast, sought new sources of spiritual power that might be accessed in order to combat the ills that came with colonization, such as alcohol and disease.Through extensive research, especially in the Moravian records of day-to-day life, Wheeler offers an understanding of the lived experience of Mohican communities under colonialism. She complicates the understanding of eighteenth-century American Christianity by demonstrating that mission programs were not always driven by the destruction of indigenous culture and the advancement of imperial projects. In To Live upon Hope, Wheeler challenges the prevailing view of accommodation or resistance as the two poles of Indian responses to European colonization; colonialism placed severe strains on native peoples, yet Indians also exercised a level of agency and creativity that aided in their survival.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aCongregational churchesxMissionszMassachusettszStockbridgexHistory. 0aMahican IndiansxMissionsxHistoryy18th century. 0aMoravian IndiansxMissionszNew York (State)zShekomeko SitexHistory. 0aStockbridge IndiansxMissionszMassachusettszStockbridgexHistory. 4aNative American Studies. 4aReligious Studies. 4aU.S. History.  achristian mission, native american indoctrination, mohican mission experience, mohican adaptation, mohican history, northeast indian communities, native communities, native religious history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146348840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801463488423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801463488/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles